Pebbles

Target IP: 192.168.152.52

Scanning


There are five TCP ports open on the target machine. There are three different HTTP applications running on the target machine.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. Trying different combinations of default credentials did not work. And the source-code does not contain anything useful.

Port 8080: HTTP

The default Tomcat webpage is displayed for this application. I performed a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://192.168.152.52:8080/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,txt and found the interesting result above. The /WEB-INF contains the file web.xml but I do not have permission to access it.


The directory /zm is interesting. The webpage above is displayed. The version and application name of this application is ZoneMinder v1.29.


Doing a Google search for this application version shows it has multiple vulnerabilities with one being LFI.


By using the payload http://192.168.152.52:3305/zm/index.php?view=file&path=../../../../../../../etc/passwd, I can access the /etc/passwd file on the target machine. There is a user called sally. I tried to obtain the SSH key of this user, but I had no luck. I tried to find any log files that I could poison, but I could not find anything.

Exploitation & Flag


I used the SQL injection exploit PoC I found from enumeration. I saved the HTTP request to the /zm/ in a file called req.txt and changed it to POST request. Using this, I used sqlmap to crack the password of user admin. However, spraying the password admin did not work for sally and root against SSH and the login form.


Using the command sqlmap -r /home/kali/Desktop/Lab-Resource/Revisit/Pebbles/req.txt --os-shell, I obtained a root shell on the target machine to read the proof.txt flag. I could have escalated to a reverse shell connection.
